# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: deskstar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:deskstar/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:deskstar/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata has developed a Distributed Storage System (DSS) technology designed to solve the scalability and reliability problems traditional storage systems face, by taking advantage of the introduction of large capacity SATA drives and solid state disk.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The entire system is permanently monitored and data integrity is constantly checked.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] As a result, bit errors on disks are proactively healed before they become an issue to the user.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata's AmpliStor distributes and stores data redundantly across a large number of disks.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The algorithm that AmpliStor uses first puts the data into an object and then stores the data across multiple disks in the AmpliStor system.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] By storing the data as an object, Amplidata can reconstruct the original data from any of the disks on which the data within the object resides.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata was acquired in March 2015 by HGST, a Western Digital subsidiary.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata was founded in 2008 by Wim De Wispelaere (CEO) and Wouter Van Eetvelde (COO).
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The company was initially funded by Kristof De Spiegeleer.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The two founders started the company to address some of the inherent weaknesses of high capacity disk systems, such as performance, bit error rates, mean time between failures and RAID rebuild times which have not improved sufficiently to keep up with the explosion of digital storage needs.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The company's headquarters are in Lochristi, near Gent in Belgium.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] De Spiegeleer founded Racktivity, Datacenter Technologies, Hostbasket and Dedigate and has been quoted as a proponent for European adoption of cloud computing.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] De Spiegeleer is also the CEO of Incubaid, which focuses on developing technology ventures via cloud computing and green data centers.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Active member companies of Incubaid include: Amplidata, Ractivity, A-Server, Dacentec.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Incubaid owns the automation framework used as the foundation for all the technologies that member companies create.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata employs about 50 data storage experts.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Some employees of Amplidata were employed by DataCenter Technologies, which was acquired by Symantec in 2005 and Q-layer, which became part of Sun Microsystems in 2009.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] In May 2010, Amplidata finalized the first round of venture capital funding worth 2.5 million euros, secured by Big Bang Ventures.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Big Bang Ventures is known for specializing in funding for start-ups and strives to provide expertise and connections to entrepreneurs in the technology sector.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] According to CEO and Founder De Wispelaere, Amplidata needed the funding to boost sales and marketing activities in Europe.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] In September 2010, Amplidata closed a US$6 million funding round with investors Big Bang Ventures, Endeavour Vision and Swisscom Ventures.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Following the funding, Amplidata announced the opening of a U.S. headquarters in Redwood City.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] However, the company does not plan to relocate its R&D departments, which are located in Belgium and Egypt.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] On March 3, 2015, it was announced that Amplidata was to be acquired by HGST, a Western Digital subsidiary.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The financial terms of the acquisition were not disclosed.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The company has become known for developing unbreakable storage systems.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata's Optimized Object Storage system enables customers to build large-scale online storage systems that aim to meet the highest reliability and availability requirements at the lowest cost.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata was designed to change the way data is stored.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The company's patent-pending BitSpread encoding technology was created to offer the scalability and ease of use of a next-generation RAIN grid, while striving to create a 10,000 times more reliable alternative to RAID.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Through more efficient usage of power and raw storage capacity, Amplidata works to drastically decrease the storage cost.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata is known for easily scaling up to tens of Petabytes.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata technology aims to overcome the limitations of RAID by the increasing length of time required to rebuild larger capacity drives.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Rebuild times for 2TB drives are already known to take four hours or longer to complete, and in some cases—depending on how busy the storage system is—it can take days for a rebuild.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] There is also the need to keep all disks in a RAID group spinning so no power savings can be realized.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Spin down is likely to become more important in the years to come as more data is archived to disk, with it likely becoming a function of the storage array to intelligently manage and place the archived data on these drives—as opposed to the software—to facilitate the spin-down of drives.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata works to reduce the risk for data loss from one event in years—as measured on current storage systems—to one in thousands of years.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Its DSS architecture was developed to ensure that a failure of a component such as a disk, storage node or even a full rack has no impact on data availability and a minimal impact on data redundancy.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] The technology enables data availability and reliability through an ability to reconstruct data from a subset of the originally stored disks.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata technologies that target cloud providers include BitSpread, BitDynamics and BitLog.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Amplidata's technology addressing the end of RAID is BitSpread.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] It is a RAID replacement technology based on erasure coding that spreads data and parity out across multiple nodes in the storage grid.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] It aims to greatly minimize the impact of a node or disk failure.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Customers can configure availability based on their needs and can have multiple availability policies within a single storage system.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Recovery of a drive or node is comparatively very fast, unlike RAID.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] BitDynamics provides the storage cluster with scalability and self-healing.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] It performs proactive self-verification of disk bit errors and then automatically heals that disk block or entire disk as needed.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] This aims to reduce the amount of work that BitSpread needs to do on a component failure and is expected to improve overall system reliability.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] BitLog leverages idle power on the connecting host by using local SSD and HDD cache to provide continuous logged sequential writes from the host to the storage.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Then, in turn, it will give high random read performance with the SSD cache, local in the application server for the most frequently accessed data.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] Meaning that a hot file does not even need to go across the storage network, it can be delivered directly from the application server.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] In addition, BitLog includes thin provisioning, unlimited snapshots, writeable clones and out-of-band optimization.
[src:deskstar/amplidata] AmpliStor product provides object storage for petabyte-scale, unstructured data applications.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] Originally named Knox Software, the company was founded in 1996 in France by Michel Gouget, along with Michel Colzi, Nordine Kherif, and Arnaud Spicht together with Marketing Exec Phillippe Roussel.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] First incorporated in San Jose, California, the company was reincorporated in France after a $4 million Series-A investment in 2004 from SPEF Ventures (Banque Populaire) and Crédit Agricole Private Equity; this was followed by a $3 million Series-B investment by the same investors in 2007.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] The firm's backup software has been released in several successive products.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] In 2009 the company released the product as a system image for VMware virtual machines.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] In 2009 the company acquired intellectual property and engineering resources from Kadena Systems in a deal that added source-based data deduplication to the software.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] The technology uses a sliding window approach to identify duplicate data which checks the data stream one byte at a time until it finds blocks that match what the application has seen before.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] The current version, 9.0, automatically adjusts block sizes based on file type in order to maximize dedupe ratios.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] Licenses for the company's products have generally been "for fee" licenses, but beginning in 1998, it has made available a limited-capability free version.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] The first version, Arkeia Light, was available from 1998 to 2003.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] The current free version, called Arkeia Network Backup Free Use Edition, is available for download on the company’s website.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] In addition, an Ubuntu 8.04 LTS repository was released as a no-cost, small-network package in 2009.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] The firm's backup appliance, originally called EdgeFort and now Arkeia Backup Appliance, was released in 2007, and has also had several versions.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] It allows backup administrators to remotely manage backup operations at remote sites without sending data back to headquarters over the WAN.
[src:deskstar/arkeia-software] It was reviewed by *Storage Magazine* in 2008, in its 2008 review of the EdgeFort 100 appliance.
[src:deskstar/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:deskstar/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:deskstar/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:deskstar/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:deskstar/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:deskstar/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:deskstar/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:deskstar/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:deskstar/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:deskstar/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:deskstar/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:deskstar/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:deskstar/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:deskstar/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:deskstar/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:deskstar/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:deskstar/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:deskstar/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:deskstar/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:deskstar/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 2010, Hitachi Data Systems sold through direct and indirect channels in more than 170 countries and regions, with customers that included over half of the Fortune 100 companies at the time.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] It was a subsidiary of Hitachi and part of the Hitachi Information Systems & Telecommunications Division until 2017.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 2017, it merged with Pentaho and Hitachi Insight Group to form Hitachi Vantara.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Itel was founded in 1967 by Peter Redfield and Gary Friedman as an equipment leasing company and initially focused on leasing IBM mainframes.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Through creative financial arrangements and investments, Itel began to lease IBM mainframes to customers at lower costs, which led to Itel ranking second to IBM in revenues.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 1977, a joint venture between National Semiconductor and Hitachi formed, and was contracted by Itel to manufacture IBM-compatible mainframes branded as Advanced Systems.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] After initial success shipping 200 such systems and net profits of $73 million, Itel increased investments and personnel to market its Advanced Systems brand.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] When Itel requested lower prices to compete with IBM, the CEO of National Semiconductor Charlie Sporck, persuaded Itel to commit to long-term contracts with National Semiconductor and Hitachi.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] When news leaked that IBM was releasing a superior line of computers, customers held back purchases of Itel goods, causing Itel's inventory to build up drastically.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Hitachi agreed to Itel's request to cut back on shipment, but National Semiconductor insisted that National had blackmailed Itel.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 1979, Redfield was forced to resign as CEO.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] National Semiconductor took over Itel Advanced Systems' sales and marketing divisions.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] National Semiconductor renamed the National Advanced Systems (NAS) division, assembling and selling IBM-compatibles where the central processing unit (CPU) was imported from Hitachi.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] National and Hitachi relied upon IBM's gradual and restrained roll-out of newer models to support IBM's technology and market share, which supported NAS's occasional successes.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] National Semiconductor and its subsidiary NAS were sued in 1983 by IBM for $2.5 billion on charges of using computer technology secrets stolen from IBM, as the result of an investigation by the United States Government into National's collaboration with Hitachi.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Hitachi settled with IBM and licensed the mainframe operating system software from IBM.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 1983, NAS ceased manufacturing its line of mainframes (which had Hitachi processors) and became a reseller of Hitachi's mainframe and data storage products.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems (HDS) was founded in 1989 when Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) acquired National Advanced Systems (NAS) from National Semiconductor and renamed it Hitachi Data Systems.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Before that, the origins of the company had a history that stretched back to Itel, an early player in the mainframe market.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Intel's Computer Products Group sold National Semiconductors' IBM plug compatible mainframes.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 1979 National Semiconductor took over Itel and formed National Advanced Systems (NAS).
[src:deskstar/bluearc] NAS shifted from manufacturing mainframes and began marketing systems from Hitachi.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 1999, Hitachi bought out EDS's share, and HDS became a wholly owned subsidiary of Hitachi.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] For many years, HDS sold Hitachi IBM plug-compatible mainframes and storage systems, but in 2000, it exited the mainframe business and shifted its focus to enterprise storage.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] On February 28, 1989, National Semiconductor and Hitachi announced their agreement that Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) would jointly acquire NAS for $398 million in cash, of which Hitachi would own 80%.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Memorex Telex and National had earlier, on January 10, 1989, announced plans on a joint venture "under which each company would own half of the unit and National would get $250 million plus four million shares of Memorex Telex".
[src:deskstar/bluearc] By that time, Memorex Telex was able to arrange financing for the deal, but National had already accepted the Hitachi–EDS deal.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] The acquisition was envisaged to provide Hitachi with a better presence in the United States to compete with IBM.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] The entity was renamed Hitachi Data Systems (HDS).
[src:deskstar/bluearc] On January 29, 1999, Hitachi announced it would take over EDS' stake in HDS, appointing Jun Naruse as CEO of its new subsidiary.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Naruse was an engineer with the RAID Systems Division who was involved in developing storage systems.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Having total control of the company, Hitachi infused Hitachi Data Systems with its corporate culture, ethics, and practices.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] On April 6, 2000, Hitachi Data Systems announced a re-organization to focus on storage systems rather than mainframes.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Shortly thereafter (June 26, 2000), the first HDS storage product was unveiled, the Freedom Storage Lightning 9900, featuring the crossbar switched architecture to interconnect memory, disks, servers, and other external devices instead of the traditional bus architecture.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In addition to HDS sales, HP OEM’d and Sun resold the 9900 and succeeding generations, which had additional capabilities such as virtualization of external Hitachi and third-party storage systems to form storage pools.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In January 2001, HDS announced the Thunder 9200, a mid-range modular storage system aimed at the small and medium business market, sold mainly through resellers.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems high-end and mid-range modular storage systems were complemented by software for storage management, content management, business continuity, replication, data protection, and IT operations.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 2002, Hitachi acquired Comstock Systems Corp, and analysts estimated that the acquisition would lead to a 35% percent market share.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] HDS moved to use the term cloud computing, culminating with an announcement on October 25, 2011.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In August 2014, in partnership with Avnet, HDS announced cloud partners.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] The corporate headquarters are in Santa Clara, California, with business offices in the United States, Australia and New Zealand, Canada, Latin America, Europe, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] The culture of Hitachi Vantara is influenced by the values of Hitachi: wa (harmony, trust, and respect), Makoto (integrity, honesty), and kaitakusha-seishin (pioneering spirit and challenges).
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems appeared in *Fortune* magazine's "100 Best Companies to Work For" list in 2012, 2013 and 2014 and was ranked No.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] 8 in the *Fortune* list of top-paying companies in 2012.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Chief Executive Magazine gave HDS a ranking of No.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] 16 in its “40 Best Companies for Leaders” list for 2012.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems was recognized among the "Best Companies to Work For" in France and Poland in 2011.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] In 2010 Hitachi Data Systems was accredited by the Best Companies organization in the United Kingdom.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Synchronous TrueCopy causes each write to the primary volume to be performed to the secondary as well, and the I/O is considered complete only when updates to both primary and secondary have been completed.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Asynchronous TrueCopy stores time-stamped IO packets in the primary disk array and transfers them to the secondary array subject to link bandwidth.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] When the primary array's buffer is exhausted, it starts flagging tracks on the primary to be duplicated to the secondary when bandwidth permits.
[src:deskstar/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems has four types of partners: Technology, Global Systems Integrators, Hitachi TrueNorth Partners, and Hitachi TrueNorth Advisor Partners.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The first Deskstar product produced by IBM was the DALA-3540, with a capacity of 541 decimal megabytes or 516 binary megabytes; the last was the 180GXP.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] HGST continued the product line after the acquisition, selling the Deskstar 120GXP and Deskstar 180GXP under the HGST brand for a short time and selling new models thereafter.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The unreliable IBM Deskstar 75GXP product became notorious as the "Deathstar" (only one of at least twenty IBM products in the Deskstar family).
[src:deskstar/deskstar] A list of Deskstar models, including all those manufactured by IBM and HGST while under Hitachi's management.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The nine current models in production at WD's acquisition of HGST continued to be offered.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The Deskstar 7K1000.C was the last model offered by HGST.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The IBM Deskstar 75GXP (six models ranging in capacity from 15 to 75 GB) became infamous circa 2001 for their reportedly high failure rates, which led to the drives being colloquially referred to as "Deathstar".
[src:deskstar/deskstar] Due to this, the drives were ranked 18th in *PC World*'s "Worst Tech Products of All Time" feature in 2006.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] Despite failures being reported within the manufacturer warranty period of three years, Michael T.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] Granito, Jr., an American user of IBM's 75GXP hard drives, filed a class-action lawsuit against IBM on 16 October 2001 for defects in the product causing it to "crash", with both of the drives he had bought having failed within a short time.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] IBM was found to have misled its customers about the reliability of the drives.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] Without admitting responsibility, they settled this lawsuit in 2005, agreeing to pay US$100 (equivalent to $164.85 in 2025) to every user whose Deskstar 75GXP drives had failed.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The drives were known for an unusually high rate of head crashes, due to the magnetic coating soon beginning to loosen and sprinkle off from the platters, creating dust in the hard disk array and leading to crashes over large areas of the platters.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The combination of two technologies, giant magnetoresistant heads on 3.5-inch (89 mm) glass platters, are said to be largely to blame for the issues.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] A firmware update introduced wear leveling which avoids the heads dwelling too long over the same area thereby reducing the potential for head crashes.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] The same firmware update also fixed a possible data corruption due to a problem with Self-Monitoring, Analysis and Reporting Technology background operations.
[src:deskstar/deskstar] After the filing of the lawsuit, IBM unveiled the Deskstar 120GXP, and the Travelstar 60GH and 40GN on November 7, 2001.
